          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How does the indirect cash flow method work?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The indirect method starts with net profit before tax and adjusts it for non-cash items such as depreciation, then for changes in working capital, to arrive at cash from operations. If profit is Rs 40 lakh, depreciation Rs 6 lakh and debtors rise Rs 5 lakh, operating cash before tax is Rs 41 lakh. Investing and financing flows are then listed separately."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between direct and indirect cash flow methods?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The direct method lists actual cash receipts and payments such as cash collected from customers and paid to suppliers, while the indirect method reconciles net profit to operating cash by removing non-cash and non-operating items. Both give the same operating cash figure. Indian companies almost always use the indirect method because it can be built straight from the trial balance."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Which companies in India must prepare a cash flow statement?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Every company must include a cash flow statement in its financial statements under Section 2(40) of the Companies Act 2013, except a one person company, a small company and a dormant company. Listed entities file it with annual results under SEBI LODR Regulation 33, which prescribes the indirect method, so the direct method is rare in Indian reporting."
          }
        }
