<div class="gl-page">
  <section class="gl-hero"><div class="gl-wrap"><nav class="gl-crumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb"><a href="/">Home</a><span class="sep">&rsaquo;</span><a href="/glossary">Glossary</a><span class="sep">&rsaquo;</span><span class="cur">Cash Flow Statement (Indirect Method)</span></nav><div class="gl-cat">Accounting Glossary &middot; Process</div><h1 class="gl-h1">What Is a Cash Flow Statement (Indirect Method)?</h1><div class="gl-byline"><span class="ok"><svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m6 2a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"/></svg></span><span class="who">Reviewed by CA &amp; CS Team, Patron Accounting LLP</span><span class="sep">&middot;</span><span>Last updated 22 Jul 2026</span><span class="sep">&middot;</span><span>5 min read</span><span class="sep">&middot;</span><span class="lvl">Intermediate</span></div></div></section>
  <div class="gl-tocbar"><div class="gl-wrap gl-toc"><a href="#definition" class="gl-pill is-active">Definition</a><a href="#what-is" class="gl-pill">What it is</a><a href="#how-works" class="gl-pill">How it works</a><a href="#example" class="gl-pill">Example</a><a href="#mistakes" class="gl-pill">Mistakes</a><a href="#faq-section" class="gl-pill">FAQs</a></div></div>
  <div class="gl-body"><div class="gl-wrap"><div class="gl-grid"><div class="gl-main"><section id="definition" class="gl-sec"><div class="gl-eyebrow">Cash Flow Statement (Indirect Method): Definition</div><div class="definition-box"><p>A cash flow statement (indirect method) explains the change in a business&#x27;s cash by starting from net profit and adjusting it for non-cash items and working-capital movements. It forms part of the financial statements under AS 3 / Ind AS 7. It matters because it reconciles reported profit to actual cash, showing why a profitable business can still be short of money.</p></div></section><section id="what-is" class="gl-sec"><h2>What Is a Cash Flow Statement (Indirect Method)?</h2><p>The indirect method builds the operating-cash figure by taking net profit before tax and working backwards: adding back non-cash charges like depreciation, removing items that belong to investing or financing, and adjusting for changes in receivables, payables and inventory. The statement then adds investing and financing cash flows to arrive at the net movement in cash for the year. It is the method most Indian companies use because it links directly to figures already in the profit and loss account and balance sheet.</p><p>A Chennai trading company meets the indirect-method cash flow statement at every audit, because most companies must present a cash flow statement as part of their financial statements under Section 2(40) of the Companies Act 2013 — the exception being one-person companies, small companies and dormant companies, which are not required to prepare one. It is the statement a lender studies to see whether operations actually generate cash, rather than just book profit.</p><div class="key-terms"><p class="key-terms__title">Key terms</p><ul><li><a href="/glossary/notes-to-accounts">Notes to Accounts</a> — Disclosures that explain the non-cash items adjusted in the statement.</li><li><a href="/glossary/variance-analysis">Variance Analysis</a> — Compares actual cash generation against forecast.</li><li><a href="/glossary/contribution-margin-dashboard">Contribution Margin Dashboard</a> — Shows profitability that ultimately drives operating cash.</li></ul></div></section><section id="why-matters" class="gl-sec"><h2>Why Cash Flow Statement (Indirect Method) Matters</h2><p>The cash flow statement answers a question profit alone cannot:</p><ul class="gloss-bullets"><li><strong>Reveals the profit-cash gap</strong> — A company can report profit yet bleed cash into stock and debtors; the statement exposes exactly where the money went.</li><li><strong>Lender and investor scrutiny</strong> — Banks and investors read operating cash flow to judge whether the business can service debt from operations.</li><li><strong>Statutory requirement</strong> — Most companies must present a cash flow statement; omitting it where required is an audit and filing non-compliance.</li><li><strong>Early distress signal</strong> — Persistently negative operating cash flow despite reported profit is one of the earliest warnings of trouble.</li><li><strong>Working-capital insight</strong> — The adjustments show how much cash is being absorbed or released by receivables, payables and inventory.</li></ul></section><section id="how-works" class="gl-sec"><h2>How to Read Cash Flow Statement (Indirect Method)</h2><p>Read the statement in its three sections, and these are the numbers to check first:</p><ol class="step-cards"><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">1</span><strong>Start at net profit before tax</strong><p>The operating section opens here; this is the accrual profit the statement will convert to cash.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">2</span><strong>Follow the non-cash add-backs</strong><p>Depreciation, amortisation and provisions are added back because they reduced profit without moving cash.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">3</span><strong>Read the working-capital changes</strong><p>Increases in receivables and inventory consume cash; increases in payables release it — the swing that most often surprises.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">4</span><strong>Land on operating cash flow</strong><p>After tax paid, this subtotal is the headline: cash generated by the core business, the first figure a lender checks.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">5</span><strong>Scan investing and financing</strong><p>Capital spend and loan movements follow; large outflows here explain why cash fell despite healthy operations.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">6</span><strong>Tie to the cash movement</strong><p>The three sections sum to the net change in cash, which must reconcile to the opening and closing bank balances.</p></li></ol></section><section id="example" class="gl-sec"><h2>Cash Flow Statement (Indirect Method): A Practical Example</h2><div class="gloss-table-wrap"><table class="gloss-table"><thead><tr><th>Particulars</th><th>Amount (INR)</th><th>Treatment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Net profit before tax</td><td>40,00,000</td><td>Operating section start</td></tr><tr><td>Add: depreciation</td><td>8,00,000</td><td>Non-cash add-back</td></tr><tr><td>Less: increase in receivables</td><td>(15,00,000)</td><td>Working capital absorbs cash</td></tr><tr><td>Add: increase in payables</td><td>5,00,000</td><td>Working capital releases cash</td></tr><tr><td>Cash from operations (after tax paid 9,00,000)</td><td>29,00,000</td><td>Headline operating cash flow</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>A Chennai trading company reports ₹40,00,000 profit before tax. Adding back ₹8,00,000 depreciation and adjusting for a ₹15,00,000 rise in receivables and a ₹5,00,000 rise in payables, then deducting ₹9,00,000 tax paid, leaves ₹29,00,000 of operating cash. The ₹15,00,000 jump in debtors is the story: strong profit, but a big slice of it is stuck in receivables rather than in the bank, which is exactly what the indirect method is designed to reveal.</p></section><div class="gl-callout gl-callout--error"><span class="gl-callout__ic">!</span><div><div class="gl-callout__label">Common error</div><p>Forgetting non-cash add-backs: Omitting depreciation or provisions understates operating cash → add back every non-cash charge that reduced profit.</p></div></div><section id="mistakes" class="gl-sec"><h2>Common Mistakes With Cash Flow Statement (Indirect Method)</h2><p>The indirect method goes wrong in a handful of predictable ways:</p><ul class="gloss-bullets"><li><strong>Forgetting non-cash add-backs</strong> — Omitting depreciation or provisions understates operating cash → add back every non-cash charge that reduced profit.</li><li><strong>Wrong-signed working-capital change</strong> — Treating a rise in receivables as a cash inflow reverses the effect → an increase in an asset consumes cash.</li><li><strong>Mixing investing into operations</strong> — Leaving a gain on asset sale in operating profit double-counts it → move it to investing activities.</li><li><strong>Ignoring tax paid</strong> — Using tax expense instead of tax actually paid distorts operating cash → adjust for the real cash tax outflow.</li><li><strong>Statement not tying to cash</strong> — A net movement that does not reconcile to opening and closing bank balances signals an error → the three sections must sum to the cash change.</li></ul></section><section id="related" class="gl-sec"><h2>Related Accounting Terms</h2><p>Terms read alongside the cash flow statement:</p><ul class="related-terms"><li><a href="/glossary/notes-to-accounts">Notes to Accounts</a> — Explain the non-cash items adjusted here.</li><li><a href="/glossary/variance-analysis">Variance Analysis</a> — Compares actual cash generation against forecast.</li><li><a href="/glossary/contribution-margin-dashboard">Contribution Margin Dashboard</a> — Shows the profitability that drives operating cash.</li><li><a href="/glossary">Accounting Terms Glossary</a> — Browse every accounting term in one place.</li></ul></section><div class="gl-callout gl-callout--summary"><span class="gl-callout__ic">&#10003;</span><div><div class="gl-callout__label">Quick summary</div><p>A cash flow statement (indirect method) explains the change in a business&amp;#x27;s cash by starting from net profit and adjusting it for non-cash items and working-capital movements. It forms part of the financial statements under AS 3 / Ind AS 7. It matters because it reconciles reported profit to actual cash, showing why a profitable business can still be short of money.</p></div></div><section class="gl-cta"><div class="gl-cta__t"><h3>Need help with Cash Flow Statement (Indirect Method)?</h3><p>Cash Flow Statement (Indirect Method) sits inside your day-to-day books. Patron's CA-led team keeps them accurate, compliant and audit-ready.</p></div><div class="gl-cta__btns"><a class="gl-cta__primary" href="/financial-statement-preparation-services">Financial Statement Preparation &rarr;</a><a class="gl-cta__phone" href="tel:+919459456700">Book a consultation: +91 94594 56700</a></div></section></div><aside class="gl-aside"><div class="gl-card gl-card--service"><div class="gl-card__eyebrow">Related service</div><div class="gl-card__name">Financial Statement Preparation</div><p>CA-led bookkeeping, compliance and reporting for Indian businesses.</p><a class="gl-card__cta" href="/financial-statement-preparation-services">Explore the service &rarr;</a></div><div class="gl-card"><div class="gl-card__eyebrow">Related services</div><ul><li><a href="/mis-reporting-services">MIS Reporting Services<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li></ul></div><div class="gl-card"><div class="gl-card__eyebrow">Related terms</div><ul><li><a href="/glossary/notes-to-accounts">Notes to Accounts<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li><li><a href="/glossary/variance-analysis">Variance Analysis<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li><li><a href="/glossary/contribution-margin-dashboard">Contribution Margin Dashboard<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li><li><a href="/glossary">Accounting Terms Glossary<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li></ul></div></aside></div></div></div>
  <section id="faq-section" class="gl-faq-section"><div class="faq-expanded"><aside class="faq-expanded__aside"><h2 class="faq-expanded__title">Cash Flow Statement (Indirect Method) FAQs</h2><p class="faq-expanded__lead">Common questions about Cash Flow Statement (Indirect Method) for Indian businesses.</p><a class="faq-expanded__cta" href="/contact-us">Still have a question? Talk to a CA &rarr;</a><form class="faq-enquiry" action="https://www.patronaccounting.com/enquiry" method="post" novalidate><h3 class="faq-enquiry__title">Talk to a CA about your books</h3><p class="faq-enquiry__sub">Share your accounting software and we'll scope the work.</p><p class="faq-enquiry__context">Enquiring about: <strong>Cash Flow Statement (Indirect Method)</strong></p><input class="faq-enquiry__input" type="text" name="name" placeholder="Your name" required><input class="faq-enquiry__input" type="email" name="email" placeholder="Email" required><div class="faq-enquiry__phone"><span class="faq-enquiry__cc">+91</span><input class="faq-enquiry__input faq-enquiry__input--phone" type="tel" name="phone" placeholder="Mobile" required></div><button class="faq-enquiry__btn" type="submit">Get a Callback</button><p class="faq-enquiry__msg" role="status" aria-live="polite"></p><div class="faq-enquiry__badges"><span class="faq-enquiry__badge"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m6 2a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"/></svg>CA-led team</span></div></form></aside><div class="faq-expanded__list"><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a1">How does the indirect cash flow method work?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a1"><p>The indirect method starts with net profit before tax and adjusts it for non-cash items such as depreciation, then for changes in working capital, to arrive at cash from operations. If profit is Rs 40 lakh, depreciation Rs 6 lakh and debtors rise Rs 5 lakh, operating cash before tax is Rs 41 lakh. Investing and financing flows are then listed separately.</p></div></div><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a2">What is the difference between direct and indirect cash flow methods?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a2"><p>The direct method lists actual cash receipts and payments such as cash collected from customers and paid to suppliers, while the indirect method reconciles net profit to operating cash by removing non-cash and non-operating items. Both give the same operating cash figure. Indian companies almost always use the indirect method because it can be built straight from the trial balance.</p></div></div><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a3">Which companies in India must prepare a cash flow statement?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a3"><p>Every company must include a cash flow statement in its financial statements under Section 2(40) of the Companies Act 2013, except a one person company, a small company and a dormant company. Listed entities file it with annual results under SEBI LODR Regulation 33, which prescribes the indirect method, so the direct method is rare in Indian reporting.</p></div></div></div></div></section>
